column39: This semester for Brightspace, they changed the layout which made using the website confusing. Before Brightspace got changed, I was able to find all my assignments in one place, which made it easy to complete and submit, however, this semester the classwork assignments and the homework assignments were separated, which made it hard to locate them. The naming of these assignments made it even harder to find specific documents that you need. If you don't remember the name of the document you were working on, you have to scroll through all your other documents to find it, which is nearly impossible because at first glance, all the documents look the same and all start out with the same title. They need to change the layout back to the way it was before.

column47: Brightspace seems to hold too much options and may be too overloaded at times. A search function would greatly help. Additionally, sometimes, news are not posted on the home page such as Spirit Week days. The badge design is interesting but should be taken more seriously. Example being students should only get a badge for certain grades of assignment completion rather than getting a badge for every assignment. It takes away the value. There could be an award feature where scholars with a high amount of assignment completion and/or high grades for HW/tests would earn exclusive badges, gift cards, goods, and/or be entered in raffles. With a few tweaks, it could really be the push for students who are motivated but are conflicted. Of course, I am just a scholar at SEO so I do not know what goes on in the SEO administration for changes such as these. But if you need further elaboration, my email is jacel@seoscholars.org.

column72: One big mathematical idea that I learned in this class is that there are many ways of solving the same problem depending on your knowledge, skills, preference, and creativity. Frequently in class, students will present with work drastically different from mine but end up with the same answer.
column74: The most difficult lessons for me were lessons 12 and 13. I believe I have found the other lessons to be easier as I have already took Algebra II, most of the things we learned was review.
column87: A feedback I have was that one of the main focuses appeared to be logos, ethos, and pathos. However, this topic has been discussed for many many semesters and I believe that there should not be as much of an emphasis on it anymore.
column98: Though the meaning of the class is appreciated in terms of mental health and discussion, other scholars along with myself have voiced that this course has gotten relatively repetitive as the course continued. For the journal, a lot of the questions asked basically the same questions just reworded. We have pretty much been talking about identity and societal discrimination since the beginning of SEO, I wish there would be something new in the future. However, my instructor Max made this course more enjoyable than it would be if he was not the instructor.
column99: I would rotate the topic to something else rather than solely identity and societal oppression. Other topics can be learning social skills, job skills, financial management, college related topics, etc.
column101: The circle topics that I enjoyed the most were the ones about failure, networking, and the playlist on my life. Though the most recent OC topic, the OCs about failure made me realize that failure could defineitly push you far and beyond where you were if you were just doing decent. I have learned that failure is really what you make of it as an individual. The reflections Leighton requested were helpful in terms of memorizing and thinking more deeply about the OCs and I think they should be implemented even more frequently. The OC where we designed the DVD with the playlist of our life was also incredible. Though more fun than productive, it struck a feeling in my heart that was nistolgically beautiful.
column109: SEO's focus on being assertive and not being afraid to ask questions has helped me in my high school experience and life in general. The community and staff's support has contributed to my willingness to let my voice to be heard and that I do matter and contribute to the program. I am glad that this aspect has always been relevant even from day 1.
column110: SEO Scholars is overall a great program and I am grateful for being a part of the community. I believe that with the right mindset, people in need could take away a lot from this program. A feedback I have for SEO Scholars as a whole is that PMs and Instructors a like should set a higher expectation and seriousness for the scholars starting from the 9th grade. I have witnessed too many "unscholarly" behavior throughout my time at SEO such as goofing around too much in class, not paying attention, being destructive in hallways and bathrooms, and a subjective one being poor motivation. One of the primary reasons why I joined SEO was for the community. Depsite there obviously being great, motivated, and brilliant scholars, the motivation, maturity, and work ethic of some scholars did not live up to my expectation and I believe that it has stagnated certain people and certain aspects and values of the program. I understand that SEO places a big emphasis on the growth mindset and that I have defineitly noticed that things are getting a lot more strict (I greatly appreciate) but I believe that this should have been happening since the 9th-10th grade, not an exponential spike during the 11th grade.

column72: I learned how we can apply trigonometry to non-right triangles using the Law of Sines, the Law of Cosines, and the formula for finding the area of a triangle using trigonometric terms.
column73: I found using the Law of Cosines, the Law of Sines, and the area of a triangle in trigonometric terms the most memorable for me, because it was one of the only lessons that I didn't learn in my Algebra II/Trigonometry class that I find would come handy.
column74: I felt that the last lesson was the most confusing, and wasn't the greatest at explaining the process. I felt that the things taught in the last lesson could be easily done using a graphing calculator instead.
column87: I felt that writing the op-ed itself was the most engaging part of the class, rather than the lessons. The lessons felt repetitive to me but were a good reminder on standard grammar conventions and the structuring of our op-eds.
column88: I found writing the introduction of the op-ed difficult because it was hard for me to jump into writing the op-ed. Although I had a lot of evidence, I didn't form a coherent argument at the time of writing the introduction. Therefore, it was difficult for me to start at the introduction; I would have rather started writing the body paragraphs, and then return to the introduction.
column98: I don't think there was any problem with the Advisory class except that it was rather quiet at times with no one uttering a word in a conversation. Rather, I think the biggest problem was myself; I wasn't confident in sharing what I thought and my personal issues.
column99: I think making the Advisory class more inviting would allow me to open up, but I feel like I would still rather keep my emotions to myself rather than share it out to my entire class. Maybe making advisory groups smaller could be a good option and allow me to open up about my experiences.
column101: I liked both the Speed "dating" and the Mixtape/CD "lessons" the most because it allowed me to be introspective and connect with other people that I don't really talk to.
column109: My program manager advocated for me to use my planner more often. Although I did at the beginning of Sophomore year, I stopped after a few months. I feel like I should probably start using my planner again, or use the one that SEO provided, but I just don't feel like it.
column110: I rated the math class rather poorly, but that's mostly because I already learned everything taught, and I feel like the math class isn't challenging for me at all. I liked the addition of the Mathematician's corner in the workbook, but it didn't feel like the overall lessons were engaging for me. Nonetheless, I could see many of my classmates struggling, and I tried to help those that asked for help; albeit there were quite a few people that would rather play games on their laptops than listen to the teacher and would be left clueless by the time we were working on our focus tasks. For the most part, I felt that SEO was a really great community for Freshmen and Sophomore year, but because our groups were changed for Summer Academy, I felt that the relationships and connections I built with my peers was suddenly ripped apart. Now, all of my classes at SEO feel awkward because there are no new connections to be formed; all the cliques have been recreated and I don't feel like being a part of any of them. I feel like this would have worked better on a more outgoing and social group of people, but I don't think the changing of groups was successful for my group. Lastly, I don't feel like my relationship with my Program Manager is the strongest. Although X is a newly appointed PM, I feel like the connections between me and X are not as strong as the connection between me and the previous three PMs.
